{title: Girl in the Night}
{artist: Ray Price}
{composer: Written by Hank Thompson}

[G]She lives her life in honky tonks and the [C]crowded backstreet bars
A [D7]world of make believe that knows no [G]sun no moon or stars
Just the glitter of the great white way and the [C]glare of city lights
Where the [D7]music’s loud she’s in the crowd a lonely girl in the [G]night
I [C]wonder if she’s thinking of [G]dreams that didn’t last
I [C]wonder if she’s [A7]haunted by [D7]heartaches from the past
[G]Perhaps there is a story of a [C]love that wasn’t right
Now the [D7]shadows hide her foolish pride a lonely girl in the [G]night
spoken:
I watch her sit there so lonely as she [C]lights a cigarette
And the [D7]smoke rings rise but in her eyes there [G]seems to be such regret
Is she there to tempt a lover in that [C]dress that hugs her tight
With a [D7]glass of wine to pass the time a lonely girl in the [G]night